y is one of progressive base-building giving way to impulsive expansion. Throughout the final week of June and into early July, GBP/JPY ground sideways in a tight band around 213.30\u2013213.80, repeatedly finding a floor near the prior reaction zone at 213.34 \u2014 a level that registered six distinct touches and clearly attracted meaningful demand. The pair then broke cleanly above 215.57, another prior reaction zone that had capped several daily closes, and that level subsequently flipped to support, holding on the pullback from the 15 July spike high. The 214.54 zone also remains in play as a deeper structural reference should conditions deteriorate. The broader sequence of higher lows \u2014 212.36 on 21 June, 214.44 on 30 June, and 216.99 on 15 July \u2014 underpins the bullish desk read.\n\nThe intraday picture on the H1 chart reflects a pair in tight consolidation rather than directional conviction. Since the 15 July high, hourly candles have been remarkably compressed, oscillating between approximately 218.33 and 218.94 with no meaningful breakout in either direction. The 04:00 candle today printed the session high at 218.93 before retreating, and price has since drifted back toward the mid-218.50s. This kind of low-volatility coiling behaviour, following a sharp impulsive leg, is often consistent with digestion ahead of a continuation \u2014 though it can equally precede a deeper corrective move back toward the 215.57 prior reaction zone if the structure breaks down.\n\nThe calendar is empty for today, which removes the immediate risk of a data-driven volatility spike. In practice, that leaves GBP/JPY at the mercy of broader risk sentiment and any unscheduled commentary from the Bank of Japan or Bank of England. A shift in BoJ rhetoric toward earlier tightening would be the most obvious catalyst to reassess the yen side of the equation, while any deterioration in UK macro expectations could weigh on sterling. Both scenarios warrant attention even on quiet calendar days given how sensitive this cross has historically been to central bank tone.\n\nThe bullish read would come under pressure on a daily close back beneath the 215.57 prior reaction zone, which would suggest the recovery from June lows has stalled materially. A sustained move below 214.54 would meaningfully undermine the higher-low structure. Conversely, a clean break and daily close above the 219.62 spike high would open the structure toward levels not visited since earlier in the year.\n\nThis is editorial analysis, not financial advice. Trading involves substantial risk of loss.", "sample": false}